reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on March 3, 2021
reviews.reviewText: This was just what I was looking for... something simple, easy to install and doesn't get in the way or look out of place in the PC case. Corrected the slight sag that my EVGA 3070 FTW3 had and I now feel better that the GPU socket isn't getting torqued by the GPU card. Super easy to install and flexible enough to adapt to almost any card. I had to put the rubber bumper in-between the 2nd and 3rd fans on the 3070 FTW3 since the bracket wasn't long enough to catch the end of it. Still worked fine and does not block airflow what-so-ever. The EVGA 3070 FTW3 has a contoured fan shroud which makes getting the bumper in the right place a little bit harder than if it was a flat surface but I was able to find a location that supported the card and that won't slip into a fan accidentally. There is a short bumper and a long one but I used the short one since I think it provides the most stable support.I read another review that said the supplied screws were too short to go through the bracket and card. I honestly can't see how that is possible unless they sent the wrong screws to that person. I didn't even need to use the supplied screws since the original ones were still long enough to fasten it securely. I included a photo in this review to show the supplied screws -vs- the original ones so you can see how much longer they are. Should fit any common PC case.I got the red version which matched my red and black theme and very happy with the simplicity of this support bracket.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 7, 2021
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Good for the price
reviews.reviewText: For the price, it's great.It works well enough, there are however a few issues with larger graphics cards.With my EVGA RTX 3080 FTW the bar does not line up with the edge of the card. Instead it runs about 3/4" inset from the edge. This results in the bar going directly where the fans are. This only allows the rubber boot to be placed within a 1/2" area between the fans. That puts all the weight of the card on a single point that is pressing on nothing but the plastic card shroud deviding the fans.I had 2 times where the rubber bumper slid over and stopped the fans. After glueing it in place, it has not moved again. But stopping the fans could cause some serious throttling if you don't notice.My only other complaint is the obnoxious logo printed right in the middle of the bar. With a full ATX case you can mount the bar upside down to hide it. But on a microATX you will most likely have to see it all the time.I did NOT have any if the issues with the screws others have mentioned, screws not working are probably more a symptom of bad case manufacturing than an issue with the included screws. (My original case screws and the included both worked fine)All that said, for the price, I would definitely recommend it, so long as you are aware of the possible fitment issues with larger cards.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 11, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 3.0 out of 5 stars Flimsy but works - Update 12/24/23
reviews.reviewText: The bar is way flimsy and easily bent down. Pressing it up tight against the card will prevent it from sagging. But a slight push down on the card will make it droop down. As long as the machine is stable and not moved around, it will support a XFX 6800 long card. I like the idea of how it works, just needs to be more rigid. - 12/24/2023 - Update, rather it be automatic or real concern, the seller asked what could be improved. This makes the seller a #1 in my book and would purchase from them again because they asked for my feed back.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars An elegant and simple solution
reviews.reviewText: I looked at many varieties of GPU anti sag supports, many of which were the adjustable pillar variety. Those may function but they are made of metal, what happens if the magnet comes loose and it rattles around inside your case? Sounds like a shorting concern to me...Alternatively, this method is much more secure and looks more professional. It was "EZ" to install and is nicely holding my 7800XT. For my install the provided longer slot bay screws and rubber bumpers were the perfect size to make everything work.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on June 13, 2023
reviews.reviewText: so I have a fairly small graphics card then everyone probably using this but I am using a RTX 4070 FE card and as far as the length is concerned, it is slightly shorter than my ATX motherboard but as you can tell this card is fairly beefy so the sag was there, it wasn't enough to the point where it was a concern but my gamer ADHD senses hated seeing it not perfectly straight and this cured it. it comes with 2 different rubber pads to support the GPU, a short flat one and a narrower one. I decided to use the narrower one so that I can flip the bracket and have a clean look without the brand showing as well as just trimming the excess off the rubber pad to fit my desired support.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on October 10, 2022
reviews.reviewText: Got an RTX 3080 Ti in a tower-case setup. Works exactly as described. Easy to install as well.Comes with a couple of different sized rubber feet, and also 3x screws. For the rubber foot location on the GPU case, for me, it ended up being in between the 2nd and 3rd fans (heading inward from the outer case).Definitely recommended to others.

Es un producto agradable a la vista, no es tan frágil pero si se nota que con un poco de fuerza extra se puede doblar. Yo pensaba que tenía una especie de tornillo para regular altura pero sólo tiene 2 gomas quitaron que se salen con mucha facilidad que sirven tanto para la función de Soporte cómo de contacto (que no pegue fierro con la gpu pues). Y ponerla es un fastidio, ya que se agarra de los mismos tornillos de la gpu. Se me hizo caro el precio después de ver su funcionamiento.
